		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Hidden Features (Contest)<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.36)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=10198'>George "urthanz" Wilson</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=10198&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> April 4, 2003</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> <B>Bolded</B> keywords are normally noticed by all, but some are <I>hidden</I>. Cards that say &quot;spot a man&quot; were neglected until Two Towers came out.<br />
<br />
First off, we&#39;ll start with the set &quot;The Fellowship of the Ring&quot;. There were several cards that were hidden in this set, and I&#39;ll talk about a few.<br />
<br />
<B>Ancient Emnity, Asfaloth, Border Defenses, Defiance, Elf-Song, Elven Bow, Foul Creation, etc.:<br />
<br />
These cards say &quot;spot an Elf to do...&quot;. Many people overlook this and see it as &quot;spot an Elf companion to...&quot;. Most of these cards are actually pretty bad to use on allies. Defiance, Asfaloth, Border Defenses, etc. all power up Elves, but Elven allies rarely fight, so they&#39;re mainly good for companions. Elven Bow might be good for Horn decks, to provide an extra archery whenever an Elf&#39;s brought up.<br />
Some cards, like Foul Creation, The Seen and the Unseen, Shoulder to Shoulder, and Stand Against Darkness are a few of the useful ally cards. An exertion is often too costly on Legolas or another Elf companion, so this is when a Foul Creation or The Seen and the Unseen are useful. Exertions on allies are generally easy, and don&#39;t have many consequences. Shoulder to Shoulder abuses the power to heal companions, so it is actually a generous card. Unfortunately with Grima, it&#39;s almost completely useless. </B><br />
<br />
Rumil:<br />
<br />
This card, like the others, is pretty obvious, but some players may not think of certain cards as Orcs. When playing Rumil, ALWAYS remember what an Orc consists of: Isenorcs, Mordor Orcs, Moria Orcs. With Warg-Riders popular in the present scene, Rumil is actually a good consideration.<br />
<br />
<B>The Nine Walkers:<br />
<br />
Another minor play on words, but there are a few races in the tournament scene these days. An Ent will be -2 when first brought out. </B><br />
<br />
Armor, Coat of Mail, Great Shield...:<br />
<br />
The fact that Armor can go on Rohan men is VERY useful, and many Rohan players use it. With Rohan, you are fine with playing a few Gondor cards. Grima must spot 4 cultures, so Gondor, Rohan, and Hobbit is perfectly fine. Coat of Mail is the same as Heavy Chain basically, and Great Shield might be a consideration too.<br />
<br />
<B>Caradhras Has Not Forgiven Us, Cruel Caradhras, Saruman&#39;s Chill, Saruman&#39;s Frost, Saruman&#39;s Power, Saruman&#39;s Snows, Spies of Saruman, Uruk Spy:<br />
<br />
Observe that these cards say (ISENGARD), so they&#39;re ok to play in all Warg, Isenexert, and Uruk decks. Seriously, never make a deck for a tournament without looking for Fellowship cards, because there are always these hidden keywords. </B><br />
<br />
Goblin Spear:<br />
<br />
It plays on a Moria minion. Cave Troll or Balrog (?) can bear this. The +2 strength is decent for any Moria minion, but on the Cave Troll, it has potential to add burdens like mad.<br />
<br />
<B>Forces of Mordor:<br />
<br />
Although this card was banned from Standard Play, it&#39;s still good. Notice that it says (MORDOR) minions? Wait till the new Troll comes out. It will work with that. A possibility for playing in open format. It really makes you think. Are you prepared for Mordor Uruk-hai (Slave-drivers)? </B><br />
<br />
Orc Assassin:<br />
<br />
Not exactly a hidden keyword, but with 4 out and 2 Hobbits, It&#39;s likely that Frodo&#39;s toast. Most people think that the case would be that 1 would go on each Hobbit, and the rest would spread around, but that&#39;s not the case.<br />
<br />
<B>The Number Must Be Few:<br />
<br />
Although a crap card, you have to notice that it doesn&#39;t have to spot any minion whatsoever to play, or use its text. </B><br />
<br />
Bilbo&#39;s Pipe + The Gaffer&#39;s Pipe:<br />
<br />
These two can go on hobbit companions OR allies. This is extremely helpful for Hobbits, especially if you play Frodo&#39;s Pipe.<br />
<br />
<B>Stout and Sturdy:<br />
<br />
This can simply heal Hobbits. If you want to heal the Gaffer, or Bilbo, you&#39;re completely welcome to. </B><br />
<br />
On to Mines of Moria! This set has very few hidden keywords, as it was a small set, and this was when Decipher was getting into making its own strategies instead of letting people think for themselves.<br />
<br />
<B>Flaming Brand:<br />
<br />
This can go on any Man. This has proven very useful in open play for Rohan. </B><br />
<br />
No Business of Ours, Uruk Tracker, Wizard Storm, Demand of the Sackville-Bagginses, and Too Much Attention:<br />
<br />
These, like the ones from Fellowship of the Ring, only have to spot an Isengard minion. Isenorcs are perfectly good for these cards.<br />
<br />
<B>Southern Spies:<br />
<br />
This needs to spot a Mordor minion (again). This is leading up to something. It always does (Man-Rohan, Isengard Minion events-Isenorcs). This will be successful if they include more burden-adding and discarding cards. Eerie. </B><br />
<br />
Not Feared in Sunlight, Deft in Their Movements:<br />
<br />
Both of these need to spot 2 &quot;Hobbits&quot;. Again, Filibert, or another good Hobbit can be spotted. Not Feared in Sunlight should see A LOT of play in Standard format, as it is the main anti-Nazgul card not banned. I played it once, and at site 9, my Frodo overwhelmed Ulaire Enquea.<br />
<br />
<B>Dear Friends:<br />
<br />
It&#39;s a shire card, but yes. It can be used on ANY companion. This isn&#39;t very playable anymore, but it used to be a legend. </B><br />
<br />
On to Realms of the Elf-Lords. This is another small set, and unfortunately, Decipher made up more fabricated strategies.<br />
<br />
<B>Abandoning Reason For Madness, Can You Protect Me From Yourself, Coming for the Ring, One of You Must Do This, Palantir of Orthanc, Saruman, Servant of the Eye, Tower of Orthanc:<br />
<br />
These all require you to spot Isengard minions, however, it wasn&#39;t really hidden at this point, because Isenorcs were out. One of You Must do This is a surprising card. It used to be used for Isenorcs, but now it also works well with Archery. Hidden strategy? I think so... </B><br />
<br />
Uruk Raider/Tower Assassin:<br />
<br />
This little system of ally-killing, then cheap, strong, fierce minions has really helped out some strategies. With Uruk Stalker still to come, this is still a good strategy to this day. Surprisingly, it took a lot of players a while to figure it out.<br />
<br />
<B>Such a Little Thing:<br />
<br />
With the &quot;Spot a (MORIA) minion&quot; quality, it could be thrown in with the Balrog to kill off Boromir. This was a great card at the time. </B><br />
<br />
The Dark Lord&#39;s Summons, Get off the Road, Hand of Sauron, Massing in the East, Tower of Barad-Dur, etc.:<br />
<br />
It was apparent that since the release of Realms, Decipher knew that they were going to bring out a new Mordor type of minion. The &quot;spot a (MORDOR) minion&quot; quality will make them possible a bit more playable in the future. This may seem a bit repetitive, but seriously, you should look these cards up.<br />
<br />
On to the Two Towers. There weren&#39;t many other cool new strategies with hidden keywords, but there were a few.<br />
<br />
<B>Beyond Dark Mountains, Ranks Without Number, The Palantir of Orthanc, Seventh Seeing-Stone:<br />
<br />
These also had the Isengard keyword, and I&#39;ll stop mentioning these, because with Isenorcs, Uruk-hai, Isenmen, and Saruman out, there were plenty of different Isengard categories.</B><br />
<br />
Elite Rider:<br />
<br />
&quot;While this companion is in your starting fellowship, his twilight cost is -1.&quot; This allows you to start him and Legolas, or him and Gimli, and so on. This can be extremely helpful in a lot of scenarios.<br />
<br />
<B>Supplies of the Mark and Valleys of the Mark:<br />
<br />
These two say &quot;spot a villager&quot;. This is proof that in the future, Decipher will come out with Gondor Villagers, and possibly Gandalf Villagers. This is one of the things people will look back on and laugh at the fact that they didn&#39;t recognize it. </B><br />
<br />
I&#39;m pretty sure that these are the most recent hidden keywords. Helm&#39;s Deep has brought almost nothing for hidden keywords. After seeing my Helm&#39;s Deep cards, and checking them twice, I was unsuccessful at finding any.<br />
<br />
However, there&#39;s one more small part. I have 2 hidden strategies to share with you. Several of you may already know them, but feel free to share other strategies with me.<br />
<br />
<B>Strategy 1: Dunland Archery Protection:<br />
<br />
Dunland has always had a problem with archery. Well there is one card that can really help them out (not Hides). Wreathed in Shadow, as you all know, is a Nazgul card. To play it, you must spot a Nazgul. However, when it&#39;s in play, all you have to do is remove 1 twilight to remove 1 archery. No Nazgul spottings or exertions. If you play a few Enqueas, Nerteas, or Canteas in your Dunland deck, you can be successful with Wreathed in Shadow. </B><br />
<br />
Strategy 2: Hate Needs Help?:<br />
<br />
Hate has always been an outstanding card, but Mordor isn&#39;t the most impressive for it. After looking for plausible ways to play it, I found the 3 archers. Southron Bowman, Elite Archer, and Desert Lord are 3 great cards. The downside is that it&#39;s a 2-turn combo, but the upside is that it can kill important companions. Southron Bowman in combination with the Riddermark has allowed me to kill Legolas at site 3 like 6 times. Try it out. It&#39;s also very fun.<br />
<br />
I hope you enjoyed reading my article. Thanks! :) <br></font><BR><font class="bfont"> <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php?id=4626&view=1&PHPSESSID=05a8f1e030a27ed02eb39d2106de8ec7'>Read the Reviews</a><font class="bfont"> | <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php?PHPSESSID=05a8f1e030a27ed02eb39d2106de8ec7'>Back to List</A></font><p><font class="bfont"> <b>You must be a member to contribute to Decktech.</b>  <p>Please <a href='/lotr/main/join.php?PHPSESSID=05a8f1e030a27ed02eb39d2106de8ec7'> become a registered member</a></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
